CHAPTER XXXVIII.

1. Vitabundus. “ Constantly avoiding.'’ The participia! in bandus implies the force, frequency, or abundance of an action. It is generally formed from intransitive verbs. Here the verb is transitive, and Livy uses the phrase vitabundus castra, xxv. 13. Madvig, Latin Grammar, 1 15.

2. Delicta] Referring to pactio. J ugurtha enticed Aulus into a remote place, where he might come to an understanding with the enemy undiscovered. But the passage seems to be corrupt, to judge from the fluctuation of the MSS.. and some editors have tried to make better sense of it by transferring it to another place, e.g·. after desererent.

3. Instruit] The present after postquam, frequent in Sallust, to give rapidity to the narrative. Oomp. Catil. 40, 57; Juyur. 66, 76, 79, 80, 84, 86.
